<H3> <TI>   EU Sees 'Arafat as `Vital Element' of Peace </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR1003152194 Brussels EUROPEAN REPORT in English 9 Mar 
94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR1003152194 </F>
<F P=104>  Brussels EUROPEAN REPORT </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "EU Appeal for Renewal of Middle </F>
East Peace Talks"; as released by Brussels Euroscope EIS 
Database] 
  [Text] Meeting in Brussels on March 7, the EU's Foreign 
Affairs Ministers made clear that the Middle East peace process 
should not be interrupted as a result of the February 25 
massacre during the Ramadan prayer in the Palestinian town of 
Hebron -- an act of violence that they have already strongly 
condemned. In a political statement issued on March 7, the 
twelve EU Member States welcomed the measures recently adopted 
by the Israeli Government to ensure the safety of Palestinians, 
and pointed out that Israel is responsible for the safety and 
protection of all inhabitants in the Occupied Territories. They 
appealed to the parties to the Middle East conflict for talks on 
the question of "the safety of Palestinians, including the issue 
of certain settlements, and to agree on appropriate measures." 
They called on the UN Security Council to adopt "an appropriate 
Resolution" as swiftly as possible and advocated the 
establishment in the Occupied Territories of "an international 
presence in which the European Union declares its willingness to 
participate." 
  The Greek Foreign Minister and current President of the EU 
Council of Ministers, Carolos Papoulias, said after the debate 
on the Middle East that all his colleagues agreed on the need to 
support the case of the PLO leader, Yasir 'Arafat, who is viewed 
as a vital element in the peace process. 

</TEXT>

