<H3> <TI>   Kinkel Notes FDP-SPD Common Views in Foreign Policy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1103094294 Hamburg DPA in German 0300 GMT 11 Mar 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1103094294 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Hannover (DPA) -- FRG Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel, 
Free Democratic Party of Germany [FDP], sees essential common 
points with the Social Democratic Party of Germany [SPD] in 
foreign policy. In an interview with NEUE PRESSE (Friday [11 
March] edition), which is published in Hannover, the foreign 
minister stated that "it is correct: There are essential points 
in foreign policy where we are indeed in complete agreement with 
the SPD." Kinkel cited European policy as an example. 
  However, the controversy about international Bundeswehr 
missions is an absolutely central issue that threatens to harm 
Germany because of the SPD blockade, the FDP politician said. 
There, the SPD must "bring itself to change course." Even a 
clarifying ruling by the Federal Constitutional Court does not 
release "the SPD from its share of responsibility for finding a 
political solution for the necessary amendment to the Basic Law 
regarding Bundeswehr missions." Germany has every reason to 
strengthen the United Nations in terms of organization, 
personnel, and finances, Kinkel said. 
  (The interview was prereleased to DPA in an editorial 
version). 

</TEXT>

