<H3> <TI>   Employers Claim Insurance Decision `Unacceptable' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1003172594 Hamburg DPA in German 1459 GMT 10 Mar 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1003172594 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Cologne (DPA) -- On Thursday [10 March], the 
employers described the mediating committee's resolution on 
nursing-care insurance as "the most severely wrong decision in 
decades." Even now, because of the excessive social costs, the 
introduction of additional social insurance to be financed 
through compensation by employers and employees alike is 
economically unacceptable, they said in a first reaction in 
Cologne. It will be "fatal for the labor market." Moreover, 
additional burdens would be shifted onto future generations that 
will be impossible to bear in view of demographic developments. 
  "Thinking in terms of political prestige rather than 
economic 
reason has been the decisive factor," the Federal Association of 
German Employers Associations said in its first comment on the 
Bonn resolution. What is particularly disappointing is that, 
with the agreement on compensation, the firm promise has not 
been honored to define bindingly in advance the compensation for 
employers' contributions for the second stage, too. "Since 
industry and labor in the major economic areas are making a 
considerable contribution to the protection of Germany as an 
economic center, these efforts are now being undermined by the 
state's social policy." 

</TEXT>

