<H3> <TI>   Fabbri Notes Europe `At Last Awakened' in Bosnia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR1103095194 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 2050 GMT 10 
Mar 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR1103095194 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Bosnia/Italy: Fabbri, `Finally </F>
Europe Has Awakened'"] 
  [Text] Bari, 10 Mar (ANSA) -- When the European states some 
days ago called for a NATO intervention in Bosnia, Italian 
Defense Minister Fabio Fabbri today said he felt relief that 
Europe had at last awakened. 
  Taking part in a debate here Thursday [10 March] evening, 
Fabbri said he would not want it said in years to come that 
Europe had been guilty of appeasement when faced with a 
situation in the former Yugoslavia that smacked of the Middle 
Ages and of the Nazi Holocaust, and the minister reiterated 
Italy's readiness to send soldiers into Bosnia if the United 
Nations advanced such a request and if all the factions in the 
field agreed. For the moment, however, no such official request 
had been forthcoming, he noted. 
  Fabbri said that the firmer stance taken by Europe had eased 
the stranglehold on Sarajevo and halted the massacres underway 
there and he was confident that peace prospects had been 
enhanced. 
  Asked about possible reprisal action against bases on 
Italian 
soil, the defense minister said that the allied forces were able 
to moniter both naval and air space and to throw up a virtually 
impenetrable shield if the need arises. There is always a risk 
of terrorist attacks but security has been bolstered at all the 
bases, he added. 

</TEXT>

