<H3> <TI>   Emphasizes NATO's Role in Peacekeeping </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR1103101494 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 2150 GMT 10 
Mar 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR1103101494 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Fabbri on Italy and Peace Missions"] </F>
  [Text] Bari, 10 Mar (ANSA) -- The end of the Cold War and 
the balance of terror has multiplied the number of hotspots in 
the world and therefore a western foreign policy must be 
maintained, while hanging on to the role of NATO, according to 
Italian Defense Minister Fabio Fabbri Thursday [10 March]. 
  Addressing a meeting here on Puglia, Land of Peace Facing 
the 
East, Fabbri recalled the withdrawal today of Italian soldiers 
from Mogadishu and the meager results obtained in Somalia, in 
part because a plethora of contingents were sent in that had 
never before worked together, he said. For him, the only 
organization capable of carrying out a pacification effort and 
of implementing United Nations' decisions was NATO, whose role, 
he insisted, had certainly not ended with the end of the Warsaw 
Pact. 
  Within the general framework, Italian action must be 
developed with regard to the following three scenarios to the 
east: Eastern Europe, the Balkans and the Mediterranean area, 
and the Middle East. 
  The minister lauded "the extraordinary commitment" of 
Italian 
Armed Forces in peacekeeping missions abroad and specifically 
mentioned the success of the missions in Mozambique and in 
Albania. He also recalled the ten Italian soldiers who died in 
the Horn of Africa. 

</TEXT>

