<H3> <TI>   Pope Praises UN Work in Bosnia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR1103101594 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1842 GMT 10 
Mar 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR1103101594 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Bosnia/Vatican: Pope Praises the UN </F>
Protection Force"] 
  [Text] Vatican City, 10 Mar (ANSA) -- Pope John Paul II 
today praised the work being done by United Nations forces in 
Bosnia and solemnly reaffirmed the Holy See's pledge to do 
whatever was in its power to encourage the search for peace with 
respect for the people themselves, and for their family, social 
and religious life. 
  The occasion for these remarks today was the pope's meeting 
here with a group of soldiers from a Canadian regiment on its 
way home from a stint in Bosnia as part of the UN peacekeeping 
force. 
  The pope said he wished to underscore his great esteem for 
the UN forces from diverse nations which are helping to limit, 
despite extremely difficult conditions, the fighting underway in 
Bosnia and who are doing everything possible to move that 
country closer to peace. 
  The pontiff praised their perseverance and dedication in 
serving as "efficient agents of international solidarity." 
  He told the Canadians that their presence had allowed 
humanitarian aid to reach populations which had been reduced, 
"through interminable sieges and fighting," to living under 
material and psychological conditions pushed to the very limits 
of what is humanly bearable. 
  Without the presence in Bosnia of United Nations forces, the 
situation in that war-torn land would be even more tragic than 
it is already, the pope concluded. 

</TEXT>

