<H3> <TI>   Spaventa Views Economic Growth, Interest Rates </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR1003150794 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1315 GMT 10 
Mar 94--FOR OFFICIAL ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR1003150794 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Budget Minister on Growth Figures, </F>
Interest Rates"] 
  [Text] Rome, 10 Mar (ANSA) -- Budget Minister Luigi 
Spaventa on Thursday [10 March] conceded that growth this year 
will be lower than forecasts made a few months ago but said he 
was encouraged by optimistic figures released yesterday by the 
private employers' association, Confindustria [General 
Confederation of Italian Industry]. 
  "It is a certain fact" that growth will be lower than 
expected in 1994, Spaventa said on the sidelines of a conference 
here, but if gross domestic product does increase even by just 
1.4 percent, as predicted by Confindustria, it would be a 
"consistent" improvement and would "produce noticeable effects." 
  Spaventa appeared wary of comments by International Monetary 
Fund officials, who said the government will be forced to 
approve additional austerity measures in spring to offset a 
runaway deficit. "I am against so-called clinical measures aimed 
at patching up the differences in forecast growth caused by 
international economic cycles," Spaventa said. 
  He admitted that "the last word will be up to the IMF," 
which 
will probably recommend new measures to contain spending and 
possibly some indirect tax increases. 
  But interest rates are the key to balancing state finances, 
according to Spaventa: "The battle against the public debt will 
be fought with interest rates," he said. 
  As for the effects in Italy of recovery in other countries, 
Spaventa said he was pleased to see that the German central bank 
had not increased interest rates along with growing monetary 
mass; "in the past they would not have hesitated to do so." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

