<H3> <TI>   Alcatel Bell Wins Orders in Russia, South Korea </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR1003150594 Brussels LA LIBRE BELGIQUE in French 10 Mar 94 
p 13 </F>

<F P=103> BR1003150594 </F>
<F P=104>  Brussels LA LIBRE BELGIQUE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Bell Gets Big Contract -- Alcatel </F>
Bell Wins Orders for Half a Billion Belgian Francs"] 
  [Text] Alcatel Bell, the Belgian subsidiary of the 
Alcatel-Alsthom group, said on Wednesday [9 March] that it had 
won two contracts in the modernization of the public telephone 
exchange network in the region of Kaliningrad, a port on the 
Baltic. The total value of the projects is $15 million, or 
532.5 million Belgian francs. These contracts were signed by 
LenBell, a Russian company in which Alcatel Bell is the majority 
shareholder. They concern the delivery of 50,000 telephone 
lines of the Alcatel 1000 System 12 type to a mixed 
Franco-Russian company. 
  The order will be spread over four years and involves the 
delivery of a combined international-interurban-local exchange 
and several local exchanges, distant subscriber units, 
analog-numerical conversion equipment and material for 
transmission by fiber optics and electromagnetic waves. The 
first combined exchange will be put into service next September. 
  Last year Alcatel Bell and LenBell had already signed 
contracts for the delivery and installation of 84,000 phone 
lines in the cities of Novosibirsk, Kostroma, Dubno, Ufa, 
Moscow, Voronezh, and Pakov [as published]. Most of the 
exchanges will be delivered before the end of 1994. 
<H5>  And in Korea too </H5>
  On Wednesday Alcatel Bell also announced winning a 140 
million Belgian franc contract in South Korea. Signed with 
Dacom Corporation, the contract also concerns the delivery of an 
Alcatel 1000 System 12 program. "This contract is the result of 
an international public call for tenders," a company press 
release stressed. The company headquarters are in Antwerp. 

</TEXT>

