<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kinkel Tells SPD To End Blocking Military Abroad </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1103111094 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 0143 GMT 11 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1103111094 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Hanover (DDP/ADN) -- German Foreign Minister Klaus 
Kinkel has noted "considerable common ground with the SPD 
[Social Democratic Party]" on foreign policy, for example on 
European policy. Speaking to the Hannover NEUE PRESSE (Friday 
[11 March] edition), Kinkel referred however to the dispute over 
international deployments by the Bundeswehr. This is an 
absolutely central issue, over which Germany risks being damaged 
by the SPD's blockade. The SPD must "force itself to make a 
turnaround" on this, Kinkel demanded. Even a clarification by 
the Federal Constitutional Court does not "release the SPD from 
its share of the responsibility to find the necessary political 
solution on the necessary amendment to the Basic Law on 
Bundeswehr deployment." The Federal Republic has every reason 
to strengthen the United Nations in terms of organization, 
personnel, and finance, Kinkel said. Germany has no cause to 
"humble itself." It must represent its interests, but it also 
has to realize that these interests are linked to those of other 
states. "We adhere to our culture of restraint," the minister 
added. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

