<H3> <TI>   Minister on Possible Transfer of Troops to Bosnia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1003154594 Helsinki Suomen Yleisradio Network in Finnish 
1400 GMT 10 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1003154594 </F>
<F P=104>  Helsinki Suomen Yleisradio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Finnish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Preliminary approaches have been made to Finland 
concerning the transfer of the Finnish peacekeepers in The 
Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia [FYROM] to Tuzla in 
Bosnia. Foreign Minister Heikki Haavisto confirms that an 
unofficial inquiry has been received from the United Nations and 
the matter is currently being studied. 
  [Begin Haavisto recording] For the time being it is a very 
preliminary contact. It seems that the United States will be 
sending more peacekeepers than before to the territory of former 
Yugoslavia and apparently they would like to station them in 
FYROM. The question has been raised whether consideration could 
be given to the possibility that the post of the Nordic 
battalion there might be changed. [passage omitted] [end 
recording] 
  Finland's current law on peacekeeping prevents Finnish 
soldiers from being sent to the warring Bosnia. Now people are 
waiting to see whether a debate will resume on amending the 
peacekeeping law. At least Defense Minister Elisabeth Rehn is in 
favor of increasing the peacekeepers' right to self-defense that 
would make it possible to send them to Tuzla, for instance. 

</TEXT>

