<F P=101> Sweden </F>
<H3> <TI>   Peacekeepers May Transfer From FYROM to Bosnia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1003205594 Stockholm Radio Sweden in Swedish 1645 GMT 10 
Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1003205594 </F>
<F P=104>  Stockholm Radio Sweden </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Swedish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] [Announcer] So far, only Great Britain has 
responded positively to the UN request to send more soldiers to 
Bosnia. In Sweden there are discussions to move the Swedish 
company in The Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia [FYROM] to 
Bosnia. This could take place quickly, but there are several 
problems; among other things, the Swedish UN soldiers must 
accept to serve in Bosnia. They have been sent on a 
peacekeeping mission in the FYROM and in Bosnia they will risk 
ending up in conflicts. 
  [Correspondent Boerje Remdahl] The question on whether to 
move the Swedish UN unit from FYROM to Bosnia is currently being 
studied by the government. The military headquarters have not 
yet received instructions to prepare the transfer of the troops 
there. Sweden, Norway, and Finland all have their rifle company 
and service and staff personnel in FYROM, and the redeployment 
now spoken about concerns the 250 Swedes, among others. The 
soldiers will be allowed to decide for themselves whether they 
want to serve in Bosnia. The task in FYROM that they signed up 
for is a peacekeeping contribution, while serving in Bosnia 
includes the risk of ending up in conflicts, despite the fact 
that there now is a cease-fire to monitor. [passage omitted] 
  The transfer of the Swedish company, or the whole battalion, 
can take place quickly provided that Sweden, Norway, and Finland 
can agree. It might be more difficult for Finland than for 
Sweden and Norway to send its soldiers from FYROM to Bosnia, 
because the Finnish Government does not accept participation in 
any other UN tasks than strictly peacekeeping operations. 
[passage omitted] 
  Swedish Defense Minister Anders Bjoerck says that he expects 
a meeting of Nordic defense ministers to take place in a few 
days to discuss the UN's wishes to transfer the FYROM battalion 
to control the cease-fire in Bosnia. The tasks in FYROM can 
possibly be taken over by U.S. UN units. 

</TEXT>

