<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Commentary Calls For Lifting Embargo Against FYROM </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1103112494 Athens RIZOSPASTIS in Greek 10 Mar 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> NC1103112494 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens RIZOSPASTIS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Our Views" column: "Embargo of Dependence"] </F>
  [Excerpts] The Greek Government's measures against the 
Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia [FYROM] have undoubtedly 
achieved a very important result in every way. The measures 
have deepened our country's dependence on the United States and 
European Union, something that today, one month after the 
measures were imposed, cannot be denied. What has followed the 
measures leaves no room for misinterpretation or different 
views. The Western allies who caused the problem with the 
barrage of recognitions of the neighboring republic have 
aggravated things anew by ignoring the positions of the Greek 
Government. They now come as mediators, brokers, and cool 
evaluators of the situation, with advice and threats, judgments, 
and criticism. [passage omitted] 
  The course of developments should change, even now. The 
measures against FYROM should be lifted and the stirring of 
nationalism and chauvinism should stop. If nothing else, when 
these feelings reach extremes, as in the case of the former 
Yugoslavia, they only bring war, hatred, and the bestiality of 
man. Direct dialogue with the neighboring state should begin 
now, away from the tentacles of the "protectors." Doesn't their 
involvement in the Cyprus issue over 40 years prove that they 
bring tragedy to a country? 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

