<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Criticizes European Resolution </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA1003203294 Ankara TRT Television Network in Turkish 1800 
GMT 10 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA1003203294 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara TRT Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Turkish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Announcer-read report] </F>
  [Text] Turkey has said that the resolution adopted by the 
European Parliament in connection with lifting the immunity of 
certain deputies in Turkey is prejudiced and full of grave 
mistakes. 
  A statement issued by the Foreign Ministry says: The mere 
fact that the resolution was adopted without waiting for (Gali), 
cochairman of the Turkish-European joint parliamentary committee 
and member of the European Union, to return from Turkey is 
enough to show the extent to which the resolution is prejudiced. 
The fact that the resolution criticizes the Turkish Government 
shows how little those who drew up the resolution understand and 
respect the principles of a state of law: The decision to lift 
the immunity is a decision of the legislative body. The 
subsequent steps will be taken by the judiciary. The government 
has no authority to intervene in either of these stages. 
  The fact that the resolution talks about a Kurdish minority 
or autonomy is incompatible both with the realities in Turkey 
and with international law. 
  The resolution talks about lifting the immunity of eight 
Kurdish deputies, six of whom are DEP [Democracy Party] members. 
In other words, former Prosperity Party member Hasan Mezarci 
has also been placed in the same category. This basic material 
mistake can also give us an idea about the seriousness of the 
resolution. 
  A resolution that is full of such grave mistakes is bound to 
be just another European Parliament resolution. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-19075 </DOCNO>
