<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   DEP Calls On Supporters Not To Vote in Elections </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA1103111094 Ankara ANATOLIA in English 0945 GMT 11 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA1103111094 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara ANATOLIA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Ankara, Mar. 10 (A.A.) -- The Democracy Party (DEP) 
assembly said today that as they have withdrawn from the mayoral 
elections, they believe that, "those who have put their faith in 
our party will hopefully refrain from voting for the status quo 
parties and thus give them a lesson." 
  Assistant chairman of DEP, Kemal Bilget announced his 
party's 
assembly decisions in a press conference here today. 
  The statement said that DEP was ready to do whatever it 
could 
in accomplishing democracy, peace and brotherhood, despite the 
fact that the state has removed the immunity of six of their 
deputies. 
  "The party assembly, which has decided to take the necessary 
legal actions to celebrate Nevroz in some parts of the country, 
will spend all efforts to have the celebrations in a peaceful 
manner and free of bloodshed," the announcement said. 
  Bilget told journalists that his party was not, in fact, 
calling on the people to boycott the local polls. 
  "This is not a boycott but a wish" he said, adding that on 
March 27, he will stay in his home. 
  He added that his party was evaluating the option of 
celebrating Nevroz in Istanbul, Ankara, Izmir, Izmit, Bursa, 
Mersin, Adana and Gaziantep, rather than the emergency rule 
regions. 
  He added that his party members will be in their electoral 
districts during Nevroz and large numbers of delegations from 
foreign countries will also go to the southeastern region during 
the Nevroz. 
  Meanwhile, the Anatolian News Agency learned that DEP 
members 
Remzi Kartal and Sedat Yurtdas flew to Brussels today to take 
part in a Kurdish conference. 

</TEXT>

