<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Conversion of Foreign Currency Accounts Ruled Out </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1003164194 Istanbul HURRIYET in Turkish 8 Mar 94 p 7 </F>
<F P=103> NC1003164194 </F>
<F P=104>  Istanbul HURRIYET </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Turkish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Baris Selcuk and Kemal Saydamer: "Ciller </F>
Guarantees Foreign Currency Accounts"] 
  [Text] Prime Minister Tansu Ciller has denied the rumors 
that foreign currency deposit accounts will be converted into 
Turkish lira and that exchange bureaus will be closed. Ciller 
was shocked by reports published by Turkish newspapers yesterday 
that the deposit accounts will be converted into Turkish lira 
and that the exchange bureaus will be closed. She quickly 
called Yaman Turuner, the head of the central bank, and Aykon 
Dogan, minister of state responsible for economic affairs, from 
Istanbul to instruct them to make a detailed statement. 
  Ciller answered a HURRIYET correspondent's question in 
Eskisehir, saying: "That is out of the question. Who stands to 
gain from such rumors? Even the military regimes would not put 
that process into effect. I have already given an instruction 
for an official statement on the affair." 
  Later, Aykon Dogan issued a written statement. He said: 
"There is no need to intervene in foreign currency 
transactions. Foreign currency is not in short supply on the 
markets. No pending transfer in foreign currency exists in the 
central bank or the other commercial banks." 
  The central bank also issued a statement. It said: "Our 
people must ignore such rumors and maintain their deposits and 
investments in any way they wish without anxiety." 

</TEXT>

