<H3> <TI>   UN Mediator Begins FYROM Talks in Geneva </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR1003151094 Bern ATSA/SDAA in French 1121 GMT 10 Mar 
94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR1003151094 </F>
<F P=104>  Bern ATSA/SDAA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article signed SM/NB: "Beginning of Talks on FYROM in </F>
Geneva"; as released by Bern ATSA/SDAA database] 
  [Text] Geneva, 10 Mar 94 -- Cyrus Vance, UN mediator in 
the dispute between Greece and Macedonia [The Former Yugoslav 
Republic of Macedonia -- FYROM], met Thursday [10 March] at noon 
with the Greek Foreign Affairs Minister Karolos Papoulias. 
FYROM Foreign Affairs Minister Krste Crvenkovski, will meet 
with Mr. Vance in the afternoon. 
  The goal of the UN mediator is to renew the dialogue between 
Greece and FYROM which was cut off after Athens' decision to 
force a commercial blockade on FYROM. Just before the meeting 
with the Greek foreign affairs minister, Mr. Vance said he hoped 
to reach an agreement. 
  Greece decided on the blockade in order to defend itself 
from 
"the aggressive attitudes" of FYROM, Mr. Papoulias reminded the 
European Parliament in Strasbourg on Wednesday. The European 
Commission repeated that the Greek measures are in contradiction 
with the right of the European Union [EU], which is currently 
being presided by Greece. 
  On 16 February, Athens refused the transit of goods to FYROM 
from its harbor of Saloniki and closed its consulate in Skopje, 
capital of FYROM. In order to lift the blockade, Greece wants 
FYROM to renounce its name. It estimates that the name 
"Macedonia" implies territorial claims on a northern province in 
Greece which has been called Macedonia for centuries. 
  The United States declared to the government of Athens that 
they wish to see the economic embargo against FYROM lifted 
because it "does not contribute to stability" in the Balkans. 
Washington favors a renewal of the dialogue between Athens and 
Skopje under the protection of the United Nations. But 
Washington will not put forward "an American solution." 

</TEXT>

