<H3> <TI>   Mediation Talks Fail To Lift FYROM Blockade </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR1103132194 Bern ATSA/SDAA in French 1623 GMT 10 Mar 
94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR1103132194 </F>
<F P=104>  Bern ATSA/SDAA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article signed SM/NB: "Talks in Geneva on Greek-FYROM </F>
Dispute. No Lifting of Blockade in Near Future"; as released by 
Bern ATSA/SDAA database] 
  [Text] Geneva, 10 Mar (ATS) -- Cyrus Vance, UN mediator in 
the dispute between Greece and The Former Yugoslav Republic of 
Macedonia [FYROM], had a long meeting in Geneva on Thursday [10 
March] with Greek Foreign Minister Karolos Papoulias. "There is 
room for a solution but obstacles remain," Mr. Vance said after 
the meeting in which he handed Mr. Papoulias a "document," the 
contents of which he did not reveal. 
  The Greek minister welcomed the "excellent climate" which 
prevailed during this meeting. A second meeting will probably 
be held in "the near future," Mr. Vance said. Meanwhile, "our 
representatives will meet to continue the search for a means of 
breaking the deadlock," Mr. Papoulias explained. 
  The question of the blockade imposed by Greece on FYROM must 
be "discussed." "I do not think that this blockade will be 
lifted soon," Mr. Papoulias stressed. The lifting of the 
blockade will have to "form part of an overall solution to the 
problem" of FYROM, the Greek minister said. 
  Following his first meeting with the UN mediator, Mr. 
Papoulias left Geneva for Belgrade, according to his spokesman. 
No meeting therefore will be held in Geneva, as had been 
rumored, between the Greek minister and FYROM Foreign Minister 
Stevo Crvenkovski, who meanwhile had arrived in the lakeside 
city. 
<H5>  Damaging Effects </H5>
  Mr. Crvenkovski had a meeting with Mr. Vance late in the 
afternoon. The FYROM minister stressed the "illegal" nature of 
the blockade whose effects are "enormously" damaging for the 
FYROM economy. 
  Mr. Papoulias reaffirmed to the European Parliament in 
Strasbourg on Wednesday that Athens had decided on an economic 
blockade to defend itself from FYROM's "aggressive attitudes." 
Since 16 February, the passage of goods for FYROM through the 
Greek port of Salonika has been banned. In addition, the Greek 
Consulate in Skopje, capital of the FYROM, has been closed. 
  Greece is demanding that the Skopje government abandon its 
flag, which shows the Vergina sun (symbol of the late Macedonian 
dynasty), and the name "Macedonia." This name, Athens points 
out in substance, implies territorial claims on the northern 
province of Greece which has been called "Macedonia" for 
centuries. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

