<H3> <TI>   EP Reaffirms Importance of Nuclear Safety </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR1403101394 Brussels EUROPE in English 12 Mar 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR1403101394 </F>
<F P=104>  Brussels EUROPE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "East Europe -- Parliament Approves </F>
EU Contribution to EBRD's "`Nuclear Safety' Account"; as 
released by Brussels Textline database] 
  [Text] Reinforcing nuclear safety in the countries of East 
Europe is a matter of great importance to the European 
Parliament [EP], which has followed its rapporteur Mr. Adam 
(Soc, UK) and approved the Council's proposal of contributing 20 
million Ecus to the "nuclear safety" account set up with the 
European Bank for Reconstruction and Development (EBRD). In his 
report, Mr. Adam states that the first operations done in this 
area by the EBRD in Bulgaria and Lithuania seem to meet EP 
criteria. The next operations in Russia are a test of the 
EBRD's strategy and are therefore to be closely monitored by the 
Community institutions. The sums in question were included in 
the 1993 budget but were not committed because there was no 
legal base. They are included in the 1994 budget as a token 
entry, and if the 1993 appropriations are to be used this year, 
a decision will have to be made before the end of March. 
  The EP wants the operations in question to be included in a 
strategic and safety action plan negotiated with the beneficiary 
countries (which should respect the main international 
agreements of security) and the interested countries to be 
endowed with an independent body responsible for safety. It 
also called for the early closure of the plants the least safe. 
During the debate, Mr. Bettini (Greens, It) criticized the 
report, calling for large-scale reconversion to "clean" energy, 
as Mr. Shevardnadze himself had proposed for all of Georgia's 
energy. 

</TEXT>

