<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Public Services Employees Accept Pay Offer </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1103193594 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 1632 GMT 11 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1103193594 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Stuttgart (DDP/ADN) -- The main wages commission of 
the public sector union of OeTV [Union of Public Service and 
Transportation Employees] has approved the employers' offer of a 
2-percent pay rise with a large majority. This was announced by 
OeTV Chairwoman Monika Wulf-Mathies this afternoon in Stuttgart. 
This means the wage compromise deal for the 3.5 million or so 
workers and employees in the public service sector is settled. 
The 36-man OeTV negotiating commission had earlier recommended 
acceptance of the compromise with 29 votes. 
  The employers' proposal provides, among other things, for a 
pay rise for lower paid workers from July 1994. The pay of 
medium- and higher-paid employees will be raised from September 
1994. In addition, the pay of east German employees will be 
brought up to western levels in two phases of 2 percent each. 
Employment-protection measures are also planned in eastern 
Germany. The new wage agreement will have a 15-month period of 
validity to offset costs. 

</TEXT>

