<F P=100> ITALY &amp; VATICAN CITY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sisde Employees To Be Tried in Slush Fund Scandal </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1303105094 Rome RAI Due Television Network in Italian 0900 
GMT 13 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1303105094 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome RAI Due Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Italian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] And now let's turn to Italian news: the Intelligence 
and Democratic Security Service [SISDE] slush fund investigation 
-- Fabrizio Feo reports on the latest developments: 
  The five former SISDE administrators involved in the slush 
funds scandal have all been sent for trial: Riccardo Malpicca, 
Antonio Galati, Rosa Maria Sorrentino, Matilde Martucci, and 
Michele Finnocchi, who is still wanted by the police, will be 
tried in six weeks. In the meantime, the former SISDE 
treasurer, Ugo Timpano, who was arrested last week, obtained 
house arrest. It is said that he has made the first admissions 
on the movement of funds, termed top-secret, the origin and 
destination of which were not clear; 35 billion lire per year 
and none of it under any form of control. 
  A new, sensational chapter has been opened in the scandal. 
Ten billion lire from SISDE are said to have been spent in 
order to support the electoral campaign of one of the governing 
parties. That sum is said to have come from the money used to 
buy the site of SISDE's new headquarters in Via Polli, which was 
sold to the security service for 25 billion lire by the 
architect, Adolfo Salabe. 

</TEXT>

