<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister Comments </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1203091794 Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network in Greek 0800 GMT 12 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1203091794 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Foreign Minister Alekos Mikhailidhis described the 
latest UN Security Council resolution on the Cyprus issue--both 
regarding the confidence-building measures [CBM's] and the more 
general factors of the issue--as very satisfactory and 
substantive. 
  In a statement to the Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation, 
Mikhailidhis said the new resolution clearly says that an 
agreement must be reached on the CBM's with no delay and that 
the measures do not constitute either a substitute or an overall 
Cyprus solution. They are measures that will open the way for a 
substantive dialogue on a solution. 
  Mikhailidhis also noted that the resolution clearly mentions 
that the current situation in Cyprus is unacceptable and that if 
current efforts fail, the Security Council should study other 
ways for implementing the several UN resolutions. 
  Referring to the draft document on UN ideas that was 
submitted to the two sides in the form of informal documents, 
Mikhailidhis said the Greek Cypriot side has asked for 
clarifications and has taken neither a positive nor a negative 
stance on the draft document. He added that from the meetings 
held so far between President Glavkos Kliridhis and Gustave 
Feissel, the UN secretary general's alternate special 
representative in Cyprus, it seems it will not be possible to 
hold meetings in New York at the end of March. The foreign 
minister noted that Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktas' recent 
statements do not give positive messages. 
  The foreign minister announced that Hans van den Broek, the 
European Union [EU] commissioner in charge of foreign political 
affairs, will visit Cyprus on 24 March for talks on the Cyprus 
issue and the Cyprus-EU relations. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

