<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ciller Says DEP Immunity Issue `Internal Affair' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA1103123794 Ankara TRT Television Network in Turkish 1100 
GMT 11 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA1103123794 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara TRT Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Turkish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Announcer-read report over still of Ciller] </F>
  [Text] Prime Minister Tansu Ciller has said that democracy 
means freedom but that no one has the right to violate the 
Constitution. She noted that the decision to lift the 
parliamentary immunity of certain Democracy Party [DEP] deputies 
is Turkey's internal affair. 
  In reply to a reporter's question aboard a plane on her way 
from Ankara to Balikesir, Ciller said that she explained the 
situation to the European Parliament officials with whom she 
met. Ciller recalled that a similar case had occurred in 
Belgium and that the immunity of certain deputies had been 
lifted. Turkish Radio and Television correspondent Yurdaer 
Tartan reports that Ciller said that democracy means freedom and 
that the True Path Party is the party that attaches the most 
importance to this principle. Ciller said: Everyone is 
commenting. Democracy is a regime in which freedoms and rights 
are balanced. No one has the right to help murderers under the 
guise of exercising their right to freedom. No one has the 
right to violate the constitution. That is not a state of law 
but one of anarchy. 

</TEXT>

