<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russia's Grachev Signs Cooperation Agreements </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1103174794 Hamburg DPA in German 1545 GMT 11 Mar 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1103174794 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Berlin (DPA) -- It is now up to Russian President 
Boris Yeltsin and Federal Chancellor Helmut Kohl to decide in 
what form the last Russian soldiers will be sent off at the end 
of August. "That is now up to the bosses," Defense Minister 
Volker Ruehe, of the Christian Democratic Union, said on Friday 
[11 March] in Berlin at the conclusion of a three-day visit to 
Germany by his Russian counterpart Pavel Grachev. The Russian 
defense minister said that the Russians want to be sent off as 
partners and friends. 
  On Friday, Grachev visited a Bundeswehr unit in Brandenburg. 
Accompanied by Minister Ruehe, he was observing an exercise of 
soldiers of an armored infantry battalion and a motorized 
infantry battalion at the Lehnin training area. Afterwards the 
two ministers laid wreaths at the Soviet memorial and the 20 
July 1944 memorial. Thus, for the first time a Russian 
politician has honored the heroes of the German resistance of 20 
July 1944 by laying a wreath. 
  The Bundeswehr and the Russian Army intend to cooperate more 
closely in the future in the areas of environmental protection 
at the level of Armed Forces and the exchange of officers. 
Agreements to this effect were signed by the two ministers on 
Friday. In a first stage, three Russian officers should study 
at the Bundeswehr's command and control academy in Hamburg and 
one German colonel at the Moscow military academy. In addition, 
joint navy exercises were agreed for this year in the Baltic 
Sea. Plans for 1995 include the participation of German 
soldiers in an exercise in Russia. 

</TEXT>

