<H3> <TI>   Kinkel Advocates Support for Yeltsin's Reformers </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1103155294 Hamburg DPA in German 1415 GMT 11 Mar 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1103155294 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Bonn (DPA) -- FRG Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel 
(Free Democratic Party of Germany) does not see any alternative 
to continuing support for the reform forces in the East, "as 
they are represented by (Russia's) President Boris Yeltsin." In 
a discussion in the Bundestag on Friday [11 March] about aid to 
the reform democracies in the East, Kinkel stressed "the Federal 
Government's pioneering role." By providing almost 90 billion 
German marks [DM] so far to the countries on the territory of 
the former Soviet Union, it has provided more than half of the 
entire international aid and is surpassed only by the United 
States. In contrast, Japan has spent DM46 million. 
  Kinkel said that German aid to the Central European reform 
states (except the CIS) has amounted to about 37.5 billion since 
the end of 1989. He advocated accepting Russia as an equal 
member into the G-7 groups of the large industrialized 
countries. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

