<H3> <TI>   Kohl Calls Lower Saxony Result `Serious Loss' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1403173694 Hamburg DPA in German 1324 GMT 14 Mar 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1403173694 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bonn (DPA) -- The chairman of the Christian 
Democratic Union [CDU], Chancellor Helmut Kohl, as well as the 
CDU's leading bodies have decided that Christian Wulff, the 
CDU's top candidate in the elections in Lower Saxony, is to take 
over the role of the opposition leader in the Landtag in 
Hannover. After the meeting of CDU Presidium and Executive 
Committee, Kohl told journalists in Bonn on Monday [14 March] 
that Wulff had conducted an excellent and dedicated election 
campaign and had achieved an excellent personal election result. 
In the CDU's leading bodies everyone thinks that Wulff should 
consistently use his opportunities in the group leadership in 
the Lower Saxony Landtag. 
  Kohl admitted that the decline in the number of votes for 
the 
CDU by 5.6 percent is a "serious loss" for his party. It "is no 
consolation" that the predictions were even worse. "This is a 
defeat." Concerning the results achieved by the Free Democratic 
Party of Germany [FDP], Kohl said the fact that FDP land 
chairman had changed his statement on the coalition a few days 
before the elections was certainly one of the mistakes that 
threw the FDP out of the Landtag. 
  In the view of the CDU chairman, the election result as a 
whole refuted the "stupid talk that the Germans are all on the 
point...of refusing to vote." The predictions of an attitude of 
refusal were wrong. The predictions of an end of the large 
people's parties are similarly incorrect. It is highly 
gratifying that the Republikaner remained far below their own 
expectations with only 3.7 percent, Kohl stated. 

</TEXT>

