<H3> <TI>   Money Supply Continues To Grow in January </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1103155094 Hamburg DPA in German 1429 GMT 11 Mar 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1103155094 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Frankfurt/Main (DPA) -- In January, the money 
supply grew even more strongly than assumed: The monetary stock 
grew at an annual rate of 21.2 percent. By announcing this, the 
Bundesbank revised upward the preliminary value of 20.6 percent, 
which it had published at the beginning of March. 
  For 1994 the Bundesbank is aiming for a money supply growth 
between 4 and 6 percent. In particular the strong expansion of 
loans as well as some "special factors" contributed to the 
unusually strong expansion of M3 -- this includes cash in 
circulation, sight deposits, time deposits with maturities of 
less than four years, and savings deposits -- in January. 

</TEXT>

