<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   Telekom Reports High Increases in Sales for 1993 </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1403160294 Hamburg DPA in German 1413 GMT 14 Mar 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1403160294 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Hannover (DPA) -- According to preliminary 
calculations, Deutsche Bundespost Telekom (Bonn) increased its 
sales by 8.3 percent to 58.5 billion German marks [DM] in 1993. 
"All our various branches contributed to this gratifying growth 
rate," Helmut Ricke, chairman of the board of directors, said in 
Hannover on Monday [14 March]. "According to the currently 
available figures, we have before-tax revenues of more than DM5 
billion, which is fully passed on to the Federal Government." 
Upon inquiry by DPA, it was said that there "will certainly not 
be any profit" shown in the balance sheet. One can once again 
expect compensation payment to the sister companies, but one 
cannot yet say anything about that. 
  For 1994 Telekom expects another increase in sales by 8 
percent to DM63 billion. By the year 2000 business is to be 
expanded to DM80 billion and the number of employees is to be 
reduced by 30,000 to about 200,000. This year 3,500 employees 
are to be dismissed, which will increase productivity. 
  Four years before the end of the telephone monopoly, Ricke 
drew up a positive interim balance sheet: "We have made a lot 
of progress on the path from an authority to a market- and 
customer-oriented company." The number of telephone hook-ups 
rose from 35.4 million to about 37 million last year. The 
number of cable hook-ups rose from 11.8 million in 1992 to 13.5 
million in 1993. Regarding the use of ISDN [integrated services 
digital network] networks, Telekom "occupies first place 
internationally," Ricke said. The number of channels, with 
which language as well as text and pictures can be transmitted 
in one network, has almost doubled from 600,000 to more than 1 
million in 1993. 
  By the turn of the century Telekom plans to have all analog 
systems replaced with digital ones. The exchange will be 
concluded six years earlier than planned. The average Telekom 
customer need not expect any price increases. Telekom plans to 
enter the Asian-Pacific market with representations in Singapore 
and Beijing. The transformation into a shareholding company 
will probably be postponed by four months to January 1995, 
according to Ricke. In 1996 at the latest Telekom wants to go 
to the stock exchange. 

</TEXT>

