<H3> <TI>   Berlusconi Files Complaint With President on Inquiries </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR1403153394 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1338 GMT 12 
Mar 94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR1403153394 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Berlusconi Complains to President </F>
About Magistrates"] 
  [Text] Rome, 12 Mar (ANSA) -- [Forza Italia leader] Silvio 
Berlusconi has filed an official statement with President Oscar 
Luigi Scalfaro complaining of the judicial handling of 
investigations into Berlusconi's Fininvest media and publishing 
empire, the president's office announced Saturday [12 March]. 
  Scalfaro has forwarded Berlusconi's complaint to the self- 
governing disciplinary body of the judiciary, the Higher Council 
of Magistrates (CSM), of which Scalfaro is also chairman, a 
presidential communique said. 
  The statement, drawn up by Berlusconi and his lawyers, has 
not been made public but was prompted by recent requests from 
public prosecutors in Milan for arrest warrants for six top 
Fininvest executives, including Marcello dell'Utri, who heads 
the Publitalia '80 advertising giant. 
  Berlusconi yesterday said he was writing to the president to 
raise a problem concerning judges' conduct. "The fact is, you 
cannot apply different criteria for different people. For 
certain political parties, enquiries are being shelved or put 
off. For others, on the other hand, enquiries are being stepped 
up, putting hard-working groups in the stocks." 
  Berlusconi's decision to write to the head of state was 
called into question by Milan's chief prosecutor Francesco 
Saverio Borrelli who in a television interview said Berlusconi 
was "going about things totally in the wrong way." 
  Borrelli noted that neither the president nor the CSM have 
the power to intervene in judicial enquiries or measures taken 
by judges in court cases. "They have disciplinary duties but we 
are very far away from hypotheses which involve the aspect of 
disciplining magistrates," he added. 

</TEXT>

