<F P=100> INTER-EUROPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Swiss, French Criticize Respective Transport Policy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1503093094 Bern Swiss Radio International in English 0900 
GMT 15 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1503093094 </F>
<F P=104>  Bern Swiss Radio International </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Switzerland and France have criticized each other's 
approach to European transport policy. Swiss Transport Minister 
Adolf Ogi said France was being tough on Switzerland by opposing 
Swiss attempts to resume transport negotiations with the 
European Union. Mr Ogi, speaking after talks in Crete with his 
French counterpart Bernard Bosson, said Switzerland would 
nevertheless continue to press its case. 
  Mr Bosson told reporters that Swiss policy was 
contradictory. 
He said Switzerland had voted to ban foreign heavy goods 
traffic from its north-south transit roads, while at the same 
time demanding free access for its own heavy goods vehicles on 
French territory. Mr Ogi and Mr Bosson are in Crete for a 
European transport conference. 

</TEXT>

