<F P=100> UNITED KINGDOM </F>
<H3> <TI>   India's Rao, Singhvi Begin State Visit </TI></H3>
<H4>   Rao Says Economic Reforms To Continue </H4>
<F P=102> BK1403164094 Delhi All India Radio Network in English 1530 
GMT 14 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK1403164094 </F>
<F P=104>  Delhi All India Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The prime minister has said that the Indian economy 
is poised for quantum growth and there will be no looking back 
on the economic reform process. Mr. Narasimha Rao declared that 
India will continue with its economic reform programs while 
ensuring that the government does not lose touch with the 
realities and exigencies of development for the vast number of 
underprivileged. Mr. Rao was replying to the toast proposed by 
the British prime minister, Mr. John Major, who hosted a lunch 
in Mr. Rao's honor at 10 Downing Street in London. He said a 
democratic and secular India pursuing economic liberalization is 
keen on tapping the vast potential in Indo-British relationship. 
He observed that during the last two years, Indo-British ties 
had made remarkable progress. The progress has been visible 
since Mr. Major visited New Delhi in January last year. 
  The Indo-British Partnership Initiative, IBPI, was today 
extended by another year. The IBPI was set up in January 1993 
for a period of one year to increase awareness of trade and 
investment opportunities between the two countries. The 
recommendations of the two co-chairmen of IBPI were presented to 
Mr. Narasimha Rao and Mr. John Major today. The report 
recommends for greater emphasis on the involvement of small- and 
medium-size companies. It has identified different sectors for 
business opportunities. These sectors include agro food 
processing, manufacturing technology, telecommunications and 
(?telemetry), infrastructure and environment, oil and gas, and 
industrial components. The report among other things identified 
major issues for the governments. Some of these are reduction 
in tariff, import duty, single window clearance system, 
flexibility in labor laws, and comprehensive infrastructure 
development. 
  Our correspondent Alok Deshwal reports from London that New 
Delhi is the largest recipient of British overseas assistance 
for 1993-94. The United Kingdom has pledged 239 million pounds 
to India during this period. 
  Later, in his meeting with the secretary of state for 
defense, Mr. Rifkind, the prime minister discussed various ways 
and means of increasing defense cooperation between the two 
countries. Earlier, in the morning, Mr. Narasimha Rao had a 
breakfast meeting with the lord mayor of London. The prime 
minister called upon the British investors to show quick 
decisions about making investments in India. 
  Britain has announced a 10 million pounds assistance for the 
World Bank-aided rehabilitation project in the Maharashtra 
earthquake-hit areas. During her half-an-hour meeting with the 
prime minister, Mr. Narasimha Rao, in London this morning, the 
minister for overseas development assistance, Baroness (Linda 
Chalker), said this will be in addition to 3 million pounds aid 
Britain has already given. 
  Earlier, the prime minister, Mr. Narasimha Rao, was formally 
received by the British prime minister, Mr. John Major; and the 
foreign secretary, Mr. Douglas Hurd, at the Foreign Office in 
London this morning. He also inspected a special guard of honor. 

</TEXT>

