<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Vietnam Receives Money for Smuggled Emigrants </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1403110394 Hamburg BILD AM SONNTAG in German 13 Mar 94 p 4 </F>
<F P=103> AU1403110394 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg BILD AM SONNTAG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [F. Weckbach-Mara report: "Vietnamese Smuggled to Germany </F>
-- Government Also Cashes In"] 
  [Text] Gangs of Vietnamese smugglers are illegally 
smuggling asylum-seekers to Germany with the support of their 
government. According to information obtained by BILD AM 
SONNTAG, this is stated in alarming reports by police and 
intelligence services, which are available to the Federal 
Government. 
  According to these reports, the state tourism administration 
(Vietnam National Administration of Tourism) gets about $6,500 
for each Vietnamese, who is smuggled into Germany via Moscow, 
Prague, and the relatively unguarded border. So far, police 
authorities have registered 100 such smuggling organizations. 
  To prepare the operations -- the reports say -- Hoang D. Tao 
of the Vietnamese Economics Ministry and Tran T. Ngi of the 
Vietnam National Administration of Tourism were in Germany. 
Obviously, they arranged with the Embassy in Bonn that 
practically any desired document be issued for asylum-seekers in 
Germany "for a fee." They learned what is needed from 
Vietnamese asylum-seekers, whom they questioned in reception 
camps. 
  According to information obtained by BILD AM SONNTAG, the 
Vietnamese Labor Ministry is officially propagating a policy for 
the export of Vietnamese workers -- in the hope of getting 
foreign currency for the state coffers. Bernd Schmidbauer 
(Christian Democratic Union), the coordinators of the 
intelligence services in the chancellor's office, told BILD AM 
SONNTAG concerning the police findings: "We have to take these 
reports very seriously and we will do everything to prevent a 
new wave of smuggling operations." 

</TEXT>

