<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   G-7: Nuclear Safety Possible Key to Russian Membership </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR1403140394 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1502 GMT 13 
Mar 94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR1403140394 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "G-7: Nuclear Safety, Key to Russian </F>
Membership"] 
  [Text] Florence, 13 Mar (ANSA) -- The safety of nuclear 
power stations in Central and East Europe may prove a key for 
allowing Russia to join the elite club of the world's most 
industrial nations after the Group of Seven summit in Naples 
this July, according to Italian Minister for the Environment 
Valdo Spini. Specifying that he was speaking on a personal 
basis, Spini, who chaired a summit of G-7 environment ministers 
here this weekend, said an enlargement of the group to eight 
nations would be "positive" for environmental issues. 
  Spini said the summit decided to add nuclear safety in East 
and Central Europe to the six-point agenda on environmental 
issues already sketched in for Naples. "We wanted to underscore 
a sense of alarm, without going into detail about possible 
interventions," explained Spini. 
  One consideration was that the region in question has scarce 
primary sources of energy whence an option for nuclear power is 
more probable. 
  The latest figures indicate that, even Russia, which is a 
major oil and natural gas producer, already has 27 working 
reactors for an installed power of 5,800 megawatt and plans to 
increase nuclear power's contribution to its total energy needs 
from 14 to 34 percent by 2000, bringing three new reactors on 
stream by 1995 and developing a further eight for 2005. 
  Spini told reporters that a major demand from the summit 
here 
is that the G-7 nations should supply greater technical and 
financial assistance to the Central and East European nations in 
this field. 
  He added that a major obstacle for making Russia the eighth 
nation in a Group of Eight was its economic problems, but he 
said that direct Russian involvement in the debate on the 
environment planned at the end of the Naples summit could be a 
first step to the group's enlargement. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

