<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Positions Before G-7 Employment Summit Reported </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1403151694 Berlin DIE WELT in German 14 Mar 94 p 11 </F>
<F P=103> AU1403151694 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DIE WELT </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Gerd Brueggemann report: "Jobs Will Be the Only Topic"] </F>
  [Excerpt] Detroit -- A big conference of ministers of the 
seven leading industrial nations (G-7) that starts in Detroit 
today will be dealing exclusively with problems of employment. 
U.S. President Bill Clinton, who suggested the conference last 
year, considers the meeting a first step "toward starting a 
dialogue with our international partners that will open up ways 
for sound economic conditions" for the 21st century. 
  The German delegation will include Ministers Waigel, Bluem, 
and Rexrodt. As the current unemployment problem is mainly a 
structural one, Bonn thinks that "the exchange of ideas on 
flexibility and deregulation, training, the importance of labor 
costs, as well as opportunities of labor policy" ought to be the 
central issues of the talks. 
  Bonn wants to refer to the plans laid down in the 
government's paper on Germany as a business location, which have 
been partially put into practice already, on how to do away with 
obstacles to employment by rigid labor market strategies. In 
addition, the German ministers want to ask the other countries 
at the Detroit conference to enforce the results of the GATT 
free trade talks consistently. In the long run, protectionism 
does not secure any jobs but endangers them, the German 
conference paper says. 
  With these positions, Bonn seems to be wanting to counteract 
U.S. intentions to make the Bundesbank's interest rate policy a 
central issue in Detroit. In the days prior to the conference, 
U.S. politicians repeatedly pointed out that the U.S. economy is 
on a course of sound economic growth, which has already led to a 
reduction in unemployment from almost 8 to 6.5 percent. Now it 
is time for the European and Japanese economies to be boosted. 
  In particular, U.S. Under Secretary of the Treasury Lawrence 
Summers has voiced such demands prior to the "Job Summit." 
Lower German interest rates would be an important contribution 
to strengthening demand in Europe, he said. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-19290 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu050_h_94002" </HT>


