<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Greek-FYROM Talks Expected `Despite Obstacles' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1403183994 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1600 GMT 14 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1403183994 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Despite obstacles, it appears that a dialogue 
between Greece and Skopje [The Former Yugoslav Republic of 
Macedonia--FYROM] with Cyrus Vance's mediation will begin and is 
expected to continue immediately after the two sides reply to 
the proposals presented by the international mediator in Geneva. 
Very little is known about the contents of Vance's set of 
ideas. However, there are reports that the proposed draft 
agreement has basic similarities with the one presented in May 
1993 by Cyrus Vance and Lord Owen although it has some basic 
differences. 
  According to information from diplomatic sources, the most 
significant difference is the separation of the 
confidence-building measures from the issue of the name. 
According to the same sources, in order to continue the current 
efforts, the international mediator has not made the lifting of 
Greek countermeasures a condition, as Skopje insists. Greek 
diplomatic moves are distinguished by a first phase that 
includes the formation of the preliminary conditions for the 
resumption of the dialogue and a second phase that includes 
dialogue under the auspices of the United Nations and economic 
cooperation measures between the two countries. Parallel 
meetings of experts from the two countries with Vance are 
expected in the next couple of days to discuss his proposals. 
Separate meetings between the UN mediator and the foreign 
ministers of the two countries are expected to follow. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

